Human hepatitis E is endemic worldwide, particularly in Asia, where large waterborne outbreaks have been reported (
 
  1
 ). Seroprevalence of hepatitis E virus (HEV) is >60% in rural southern People’s Republic of China (
 
  2
 ) and 4%–10% in western Europe (
 
  3
 ) and the United States (
 
  4
 ). In these areas, hepatitis E occurs mostly as sporadic cases (
 
  5
 
 –
 
  7
 ), but epidemics also have been described (
 
  8
 ). Most cases in Europe have been linked to genotype 1 (g1) virus and associated with travel to g1-endemic areas. However, autochthonous human infections are increasing in Europe and in other industrialized countries (
 
  5
 
 ,
 
  6
 
 ,
 
  9
 ). Of the 4 genotypes affecting humans, genotype 3 (g3) is the main HEV genotype also circulating among pigs in Europe (
 
  10
 ) and human infections are observed sporadically worldwide (
 
  11
 
 ,
 
  12
 ).
